2️⃣ useReducer:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::

useReducer is used when state logic becomes complex.

Instead of many useState calls, we manage state using a reducer function.

This pattern is similar to:

| Technology   | Equivalent       |
| ------------ | ---------------- |
| Redux        | reducer          |
| Android MVVM | state reducers   |
| Flutter      | state management |


Reducer Pattern

The flow:

Action
 ↓
Reducer
 ↓
New State
Basic Syntax
const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState)

| Part     | Meaning                    |
| -------- | -------------------------- |
| state    | current state              |
| dispatch | function to trigger action |
| reducer  | logic for updating state   |


Example: Counter using useReducer
import React, {useReducer} from 'react'
import {View, Text, Button} from 'react-native'

const initialState = {count:0}

function reducer(state, action){

switch(action.type){

case "increment":
return {count: state.count + 1}

case "decrement":
return {count: state.count - 1}

default:
return state

}

}

export default function App(){

const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, initialState)

return(

<View style={{flex:1, justifyContent:'center', alignItems:'center'}}>

<Text style={{fontSize:24}}>
Count: {state.count}
</Text>

<Button
title="Increase"
onPress={()=> dispatch({type:"increment"})}
/>

<Button
title="Decrease"
onPress={()=> dispatch({type:"decrement"})}
/>

</View>

)

}
How useReducer Works

User presses button:

dispatch({type:"increment"})

Reducer receives action:

case "increment"

New state returned:

{count: state.count + 1}

UI updates automatically.

..........................................
When to Use useState vs useReducer:- 
...........................................

| Hook       | Best Use            |
| ---------- | ------------------- |
| useState   | simple state        |
| useReducer | complex state logic |

