8.2 Global State — Context API:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

In local state, data exists inside a single component.

Example:

LoginForm
   └── useState(email)

But in large apps, multiple screens may need the same data.

Example:

User Info
Theme
Language
Authentication state
Cart items

If we pass data through many components, we get something called prop drilling.

Problem: Prop Drilling

Example component structure:

App
 └── Screen
      └── Header
           └── UserProfile

If UserProfile needs user data:

App → Screen → Header → UserProfile

We must pass props through every level.

Example:

<Screen user={user} />

This becomes messy in large apps.

Solution: Context API

The Context API allows us to share state globally across components without passing props manually.

Think of Context as a global data store.

Example:

Context Provider
      ↓
All components can access the data


Core Parts of Context API:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

There are three main parts:
| Part          | Purpose         |
| ------------- | --------------- |
| createContext | creates context |
| Provider      | provides data   |
| useContext    | consumes data   |


Step 1: Create Context:- 
..............................

Create a context file.

Example:

import {createContext} from "react"

export const UserContext = createContext()


Step 2: Create Provider:-
..................................

A Provider stores the global state and wraps the app.

Example:

import React, {useState} from "react"
import {UserContext} from "./UserContext"

export default function UserProvider({children}){

const [user, setUser] = useState("Ritesh")

return(

<UserContext.Provider value={{user, setUser}}>
{children}
</UserContext.Provider>

)

}

Now any component inside the provider can access the data.

Step 3: Wrap the App:-
............................

Wrap your app with the provider.

Example:

import UserProvider from "./UserProvider"

export default function App(){

return(

<UserProvider>
<HomeScreen/>
</UserProvider>

)

}
Step 4: Access Context:- 
.............................

Inside any component:

import {useContext} from "react"
import {UserContext} from "./UserContext"

Example:

function Profile(){

const {user} = useContext(UserContext)

return(
<Text>Hello {user}</Text>
)

}
Full Working Example
import React, {createContext, useState, useContext} from "react"
import {View, Text, Button} from "react-native"

const UserContext = createContext()

function Home(){

const {user, setUser} = useContext(UserContext)

return(

<View>

<Text>User: {user}</Text>

<Button
title="Change User"
onPress={() => setUser("Amit")}
/>

</View>

)

}

export default function App(){

const [user, setUser] = useState("Ritesh")

return(

<UserContext.Provider value={{user, setUser}}>

<Home/>

</UserContext.Provider>

)

}
Data Flow in Context
Context Provider
      │
      ▼
Child Components
      │
      ▼
useContext() reads data
Example Use Cases

Context API is used for global app data:

Authentication
Theme (dark/light mode)
Language
User profile
App settings

Example apps using similar patterns:
............................................

Instagram → user authentication state

Spotify → theme & playback state

When to Use Context

Good for:

App-wide settings
User authentication
Themes
Localization

Not ideal for very complex state management.

For large apps developers use:

Redux

Zustand

MobX

