One of the most influential architectures used in React is Flux.

1️⃣ Flux Architecture:-
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Flux is a design pattern created by Meta Platforms for managing application state.

Flux introduced the concept of unidirectional data flow.

Key Idea of Flux

Instead of data flowing everywhere, Flux enforces:

Single Direction Data Flow

Example flow:

View
 ↓
Action
 ↓
Dispatcher
 ↓
Store
 ↓
View (UI updates)

This architecture prevents chaotic state updates.

Components of Flux:-
:::::::::::::::::::::::

| Component  | Purpose                 |
| ---------- | ----------------------- |
| Action     | describes an event      |
| Dispatcher | sends actions           |
| Store      | holds application state |
| View       | UI components           |


Flux Data Flow:-
.......................
User clicks button
      ↓
Action is created
      ↓
Dispatcher sends action
      ↓
Store updates state
      ↓
UI re-renders

This makes the system predictable.

Example Flow in React Native

User presses button:

Increase Counter

Flux flow:

Button Click
   ↓
Dispatch Action (INCREMENT)
   ↓
Store Updates State
   ↓
Component Re-renders


Flux vs Traditional Architecture:-
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::


Traditional architecture:-
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Component ↔ Component ↔ Component

Data flows in many directions → harder to debug.

Flux architecture:

Component
   ↓
Action
   ↓
Store
   ↓
Component

Only one direction.

Flux in Redux

Redux simplified Flux architecture.

Redux removed the dispatcher and used reducers instead.

Redux architecture:

Component
   ↓
Dispatch Action
   ↓
Reducer
   ↓
Store
   ↓
Component
Visual Comparison
Flux
View → Action → Dispatcher → Store → View
Redux
View → Action → Reducer → Store → View

Redux is essentially Flux with fewer layers.

