8.5: Memoization
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
What is Memoization?

Memoization is a technique where React remembers the result of an expensive calculation and reuses it instead of recalculating.

Concept:

Expensive calculation
       ↓
Result stored in memory
       ↓
Reused when inputs don't change

This improves performance in large React Native apps.

Why Memoization is Needed

In React, every state update causes the component to re-render.

Example:

Button pressed
↓
State changes
↓
Component re-renders
↓
All calculations run again

If calculations are expensive, this slows down the app.

Memoization solves this problem.

1️⃣ useMemo:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::

useMemo is used to memoize values (results of calculations).

Syntax
const memoizedValue = useMemo(() => {
   return computeSomething()
}, [dependencies])

Explanation:

| Part         | Meaning                           |
| ------------ | --------------------------------- |
| function     | expensive calculation             |
| dependencies | values that trigger recalculation |


Example Without useMemo:- 
.................................
function App(){

const [count, setCount] = useState(0)

const result = expensiveCalculation(count)

return(...)
}

Every render runs:

expensiveCalculation()

Even if count didn't change.

Example With useMemo:- 
................................
import React, {useState, useMemo} from "react"
import {View, Text, Button} from "react-native"

export default function App(){

const [count, setCount] = useState(0)

const doubleValue = useMemo(() => {

console.log("Calculating...")

return count * 2

}, [count])

return(

<View>

<Text>Count: {count}</Text>
<Text>Double: {doubleValue}</Text>

<Button
title="Increase"
onPress={() => setCount(count + 1)}
/>

</View>

)

}

Now calculation runs only when count changes.

Real World Example:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::

Example in a shopping app:

Cart Items
↓
Total Price Calculation

Without memoization:

Total recalculates every render

With useMemo:
.......................

Recalculate only when cart changes
When to Use useMemo

Use it when:

Heavy calculations
Large lists
Data transformations
Filtering or sorting data

Example:

const filteredProducts = useMemo(() => {
 return products.filter(p => p.price > 100)
}, [products])



2️⃣ useCallback:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

useCallback is used to memoize functions.

Sometimes functions are recreated on every render, which causes child components to re-render.

useCallback prevents this.

Syntax
const memoizedFunction = useCallback(() => {
   doSomething()
}, [dependencies])
Example Without useCallback
function App(){

const handleClick = () => {
 console.log("Clicked")
}

return <Button onPress={handleClick} />

}

Each render creates a new function reference.

This can trigger unnecessary re-renders.

Example With useCallback:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
import React, {useCallback} from "react"
import {Button} from "react-native"

export default function App(){

const handleClick = useCallback(() => {

console.log("Clicked")

}, [])

return(

<Button
title="Press"
onPress={handleClick}
/>

)

}

Now the function is reused across renders.

Real Example with Child Component
const Child = React.memo(({onClick}) => {

console.log("Child Render")

return <Button title="Click" onPress={onClick} />

})

Parent component:
..............................

const handleClick = useCallback(() => {

console.log("Clicked")

}, [])

This prevents unnecessary child component re-renders.

useMemo vs useCallback:- 
:::::::::::::::::::::::::::::

| Hook        | Memoizes  |
| ----------- | --------- |
| useMemo     | values    |
| useCallback | functions |


Example:

useMemo(() => calculateTotal(), [cart])
useCallback(() => handleClick(), [])


Visual Understanding:-
...............................
Without Memoization
State change
↓
Component re-render
↓
All functions and calculations recreated
With Memoization
State change
↓
React checks dependencies
↓
Only required calculations run
Common Mistake

Developers often overuse memoization.

Memoization itself has a cost.

Bad example:-
......................

const value = useMemo(() => count + 1, [count])

This calculation is too simple — memoization is unnecessary.

Use memoization only for expensive operations.

