1️⃣ AsyncStorage:-
::::::::::::::::::::

AsyncStorage is the most common local storage API in React Native.

It works like local storage for mobile apps.

Data is stored as key–value pairs.

Example:

key → value

Example storage:

"userToken" → "abc123"
"theme" → "dark"

Installing AsyncStorage
npm install @react-native-async-storage/async-storage


Importing AsyncStorage
import AsyncStorage from '@react-native-async-storage/async-storage'


Saving Data:-
...................

Example: Save a username.

const saveUser = async () => {
  try {
    await AsyncStorage.setItem("username", "Ritesh")
  } catch(error) {
    console.log(error)
  }
}

Explanation:

setItem(key, value)
Retrieving Data
const getUser = async () => {
  const user = await AsyncStorage.getItem("username")
  console.log(user)
}

Output:

Ritesh

Removing Data:- 
::::::::::::::::::::::::::
await AsyncStorage.removeItem("username")
Example: Persistent Login
import React, {useEffect, useState} from "react"
import {View, Text, Button} from "react-native"
import AsyncStorage from "@react-native-async-storage/async-storage"

export default function App(){

const [user, setUser] = useState(null)

useEffect(()=>{
 loadUser()
},[])

const loadUser = async ()=>{
 const savedUser = await AsyncStorage.getItem("user")
 if(savedUser){
   setUser(savedUser)
 }
}

const login = async ()=>{
 await AsyncStorage.setItem("user","Ritesh")
 setUser("Ritesh")
}

return(

<View>

<Text>User: {user}</Text>

<Button
title="Login"
onPress={login}
/>

</View>

)

}

Now the username stays saved even after restarting the app.

When to Use AsyncStorage

Use it for:

Authentication tokens
User preferences
Theme settings
Small data storage

But AsyncStorage is not suitable for large databases.

For large data developers use:

SQLite
Realm
WatermelonDB

