8.8: State Normalization
::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::::
What is State Normalization?

State normalization means structuring state in a flat and organized way instead of deeply nested objects.

In large apps, API responses often contain nested data.

Example API response:
....................................

{
  "posts": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "title": "Post 1",
      "author": {
        "id": 10,
        "name": "John"
      }
    }
  ]
}

This creates deep nesting in state.

Example state:

state.posts[0].author.name

Deep nesting causes problems:
........................................

Harder updates
Duplicate data
Complex state management
Slower performance

State normalization solves these problems.

The Idea Behind Normalization

Instead of storing nested objects, we store entities separately and reference them by ID.

Normalized state structure:
................................

{
  posts: {
    byId: {
      1: { id:1, title:"Post 1", authorId:10 }
    },
    allIds: [1]
  },

  users: {
    byId: {
      10: { id:10, name:"John" }
    },
    allIds: [10]
  }
}

Now the structure is flat and efficient.

Before Normalization

Example nested state:

{
 posts:[
  {
   id:1,
   title:"Post 1",
   author:{
    id:10,
    name:"John"
   }
  }
 ]
}

Problems:

Duplicate author data
Hard to update
Complex nested updates
After Normalization

Normalized state:
......................

{
 posts:{
  byId:{
   1:{id:1,title:"Post 1",authorId:10}
  },
  allIds:[1]
 },

 users:{
  byId:{
   10:{id:10,name:"John"}
  },
  allIds:[10]
 }
}

Benefits:

Fast lookup
No duplication
Easier updates
Cleaner structure
Why Normalization is Important

Large apps often contain related data.

Example relationships:
..............................

Users
Posts
Comments
Likes

Without normalization:
...........................

Posts contain users
Comments contain users
Likes contain users

This duplicates the same user many times.

Normalization stores one user record and references it everywhere.

Real Example (Social App)
...............................

Example structure used in apps like:

Instagram

Twitter

Normalized state:

{
 users:{
  byId:{
   1:{id:1,name:"Alice"},
   2:{id:2,name:"Bob"}
  }
 },

 posts:{
  byId:{
   101:{id:101,userId:1,text:"Hello"},
   102:{id:102,userId:2,text:"React Native"}
  }
 }
}

To get post author:

users[posts[101].userId]
Benefits of State Normalization
1️⃣ Faster Updates
.........................

Updating user data:

users.byId[1].name = "Alice Updated"

Only one place to update.

2️⃣ Avoids Data Duplication
.................................

Instead of storing user data in many posts:

Store user once
Reference by ID
3️⃣ Better Performance
............................

Lookups become faster.

Example:

posts.byId[101]

Instead of looping through arrays.

Normalization with Redux Toolkit

Redux Toolkit provides createEntityAdapter to manage normalized state.

Example:

import {createEntityAdapter} from "@reduxjs/toolkit"

const usersAdapter = createEntityAdapter()

Initial state:
.......................

const initialState = usersAdapter.getInitialState()

Add users:

usersAdapter.addMany(state, users)

This automatically creates:

ids
entities

Example state:

{
 ids:[1,2,3],
 entities:{
 1:{id:1,name:"Alice"},
 2:{id:2,name:"Bob"}
 }
}
